<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: THIS BOY'S LIFE A MEMOIR BY TOBIAS WOLFF (HARPER &amp; ROW: 
$8.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Readers may find it difficult to believe that the subject of this arresting 
autobiography survived his unhappy childhood to become a highly respected 
writer rather than a convict on death row. His efforts to escape from his 
abusive stepfather and ineffectual mother lead Tobias Wolff to lie, cheat, 
steal, drink, run away and forge checks. 
</P>
<P>
He changes his from name "Tobias," an old name in his father's family, to 
"Jack" in a gesture of rejection, but he lies and falsifies transcripts to gain 
admission to the exclusive prep school his father and brother attended. The 
author spares neither his audience nor himself: He was clearly an incorrigible 
thug as a youth, but his pain is so overwhelming that the reader longs to 
comfort him rather than discipline him. Wolff's vigorous, straightforward prose 
makes "This Boy's Life" a darkly memorable book. 
</P>
</TEXT>
