<HEADLINE>
<P>
FLOATING JAILS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Local political leaders tell us they have no money for additional jails. 
Citizens complain about locating criminal detention facilities in their back 
yards, and the justice system grinds slowly to a halt because we have no 
courtrooms. 
</P>
<P>
And all the while, former warships sit in mothballs in local harbors. How does 
that figure? 
</P>
<P>
As a former Marine Corps judge advocate, I know prisoners have been held in 
ship brigs for the last several years. The repair ship Jason, and the destroyer 
tenders Cape Code and Acadia have all housed prisoners waiting for 
court-martial. If it works for the military, why not the county? 
</P>
<P>
Why not rejuvenate these decaying vessels into beautiful memorials of San Diego 
naval history and use them as county jails? We can then take the space adjacent 
to the downtown courthouse that presently serves as the County Jail and build 
the courtrooms our judges need to ease the crunch on our justice system. 
</P>
<P>
THOMAS M. CONNALLY 
</P>
<P>
El Cajon 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
