<HEADLINE>
<P>
EL CAMINO SHOCKED BY MT. SAC, 60-58 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEN BANKS, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a game that matched the defending South Coast Conference champions, El 
Camino College, against a team that hadn't won a conference game in two 
seasons, visiting Mt. San Antonio College shocked the Warriors, 60-58, Saturday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
John Moses hit the game-winning shot for Mt. SAC with 10 seconds left in the 
game. The Warriors were not able to get a shot off before the horn sounded. 
</P>
<P>
"We just could not hit our shots when we really needed to in the second half," 
El Camino Coach Ron McClurkin said. 
</P>
<P>
El Camino (15-5, 0-1) never really got its offense on track. But despite cold 
shooting, the Warriors were able to lead by 10 points at halftime, 32-22, 
because of a tough defense. 
</P>
<P>
The Warriors finished the night shooting a dismal 34% from the field. 
"Basically, our defense kept us in the game," McClurkin said. 
</P>
<P>
Trailing by 13 points in the opening moments of the second half, Mt. SAC got 
its own defense to stiffen. "We decided to play a lot more man-to-man in the 
second half," Coach Ralph Osterkamp said. "That allowed us to get back into the 
game." 
</P>
<P>
The Mountaineers (5-14, 1-0) tied the game when Moses scored with 6:15 
remaining and took the lead on a Ny Bradford lay-in with 5:13 left. 
</P>
<P>
El Camino next plays at Pasadena Community College on Wednesday at 7:30 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
