<HEADLINE>
<P>
FACES FOR THE NINETIES; 
</P>
<P>
WHO WILL BE THE FACES TO WATCH IN THE PERFORMING ARTS IN THE 1990S? NOTHING'S 
FOR CERTAIN, OF COURSE, BUT BASED ON THEIR PREVIOUS WORK, CALENDAR'S CRITICS 
AND WRITERS HAVE SELECTED THESE INDIVIDUALS IN THE AREAS OF MUSIC, STAGE AND 
DANCE, AND PERFORMANCE:; 
</P>
<P>
MUSIC; 
</P>
<P>
CLAUDIO ABBADO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By John Henken 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Herbert von Karajan may be dead, but the cornerstones of his musical empire are 
intact and have fallen into the hands of 56-year-old conductor Claudio Abbado. 
</P>
<P>
The next decade will see if another Generalmusikdirektor for Europe is in the 
making. 
</P>
<P>
As something of a dark-horse candidate, Abbado last October succeeded Karajan 
as chief conductor of the Berlin Philharmonic -- only the fifth in the 107-year 
history of the orchestra. He was already music director of the Vienna State 
Opera, a post once Karajan's and one which Abbado intends to hold 
simultaneously with Berlin. He was previously music director of La Scala (as 
was Karajan) and chief conductor of the London Symphony (Karajan had led 
London's Philharmonia Orchestra). 
</P>
<P>
There the similarities may end. By all accounts, Abbado is a quiet, private 
person and patient in rehearsal. He has championed new music and liberal causes 
-- a close friend of Italian Communists such as composer Luigi Nono, Abbado has 
publicly campaigned against Italian fascists and taken the La Scalaorchestra 
out to factories for inexpensive concerts. 
</P>
<P>
It is unlikely that Abbado will -- or would want to -- lead the Berliners and 
Viennese down avant-garde paths, but musicians who had spurned association with 
Karajan because of his previous Nazi ties -- or whom Karajan had barred -- may 
return to the Central European fold. 
</P>
<P>
Although he was the principal guest conductor of the Chicago Symphony for three 
years and reportedly had agreed to take over the New York Philharmonic before 
he was offered the Berlin position, Abbado is largely known in this country -- 
particularly on the West Coast -- through recordings. His discography lists 
well over 100 recordings, most on Deutsche Grammophon, and most of standard 
Germanocentric symphonic fare and Italian opera. John Henken 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, CLAUDIO ABBADO 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Profile 
</P>
</TYPE>
